{
  "text": "Magnetic resonance imaging of the CNS of B. procyonis NLM patients may reveal findings consistent with acute disseminated encephalomyelitis, as evidenced by diffuse, deep white matter abnormalities that exhibit a periventricular and cerebellar distribution [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In the later stages of baylisascariasis, white matter lesions become more widespread and patients may develop generalized brain atrophy (2, 36) ( Table 5 and Fig. 2 ). However, ventricular dilation, cerebellar edema, and spinal enhancement have also been observed [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Although possible in human infections, single focal lesions have not been detected, but a single focal lesion was reported in a white-handed gibbon (Hylobates sp.) with B. procyonis NLM [CITATION_6] . An infected orangutan (Pongo pygmaeus) had lesions similar to those seen in human cases, with hyperintense regions in the thalami and central white matter [CITATION_7] .",
